================================================================================
SECTION 1: VISUAL KEYWORDS (DIAGRAMS FROM CODE)
================================================================================

These keywords help you get diagrams and visual representations from AI.

MERMAID
-------
What it is:
- A text-based language that renders into flowcharts, sequence diagrams
- Supported by: GitHub, Notion, VS Code, many Markdown editors

How to use:
- "Create a Mermaid sequence diagram showing the authentication flow"
- "Visualize this logic as a Mermaid flowchart"

Example output:
```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[User] --> B[Login Page]
    B --> C{Valid?}
    C -->|Yes| D[Dashboard]
    C -->|No| E[Error]
```

FLOWCHART
---------
What it is:
- Visual representation of decisions and steps
- Boxes = actions, Diamonds = decisions, Arrows = flow

How to use:
- "Visualize this if-else logic as a flowchart"
- "Create a flowchart showing the order processing steps"

GRAPHVIZ / DOT
--------------
What it is:
- Another diagram language (older than Mermaid)
- Better for complex networks and relationships

When to use:
- Complex network diagrams
- Database entity relationships
- Dependency graphs

================================================================================
SECTION 2: DEEP DEBUGGING KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Use these when you can't run code but need to understand it.

DRY RUN
-------
What it is:
- AI mentally "executes" code step by step
- Shows variable values at each step

How to use:
- "Dry run this loop with input [1, 5, 10]"
- "Dry run this function and show variable states"

Example prompt:
"Dry run this loop with input [1, 5, 10]. Show the state of variables 
i and total at each iteration."

Example AI response:
Iteration 1: i=0, value=1, total=1
Iteration 2: i=1, value=5, total=6
Iteration 3: i=2, value=10, total=16
Final result: 16

TRACE
-----
What it is:
- Shows the execution PATH taken through code
- Which functions called, which branches entered

How to use:
- "Trace the execution path if user input is null"
- "Trace this function call with these parameters"

Difference from Dry Run:
- Dry Run = shows variable VALUES
- Trace = shows PATH taken

ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS
-------------------
What it is:
- Finds the REAL reason something broke
- Not just the symptom, but the underlying cause

How to use:
- "The code fails with timeout. Perform root cause analysis"
- "This function returns wrong results. Do root cause analysis"

Expected response structure:
SYMPTOM: What you observed
INVESTIGATION: Steps to find the cause
ROOT CAUSE: The actual problem
FIX: How to solve it

================================================================================
SECTION 3: DEPENDENCY KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Control what libraries/tools the AI uses in its solutions.

STANDARD LIBRARY ONLY
---------------------
What it is:
- Use only built-in language features
- No external packages (no npm, no pip)

When to use:
- Restricted environments
- Minimal dependencies needed
- Maximum portability

Examples by language:
- Python: os, json, datetime (NOT pandas, requests)
- JavaScript: Array, Math (NOT lodash, axios)
- Java: java.util, java.io (NOT Apache Commons)

How to use:
- "Parse this CSV using standard library only (no Pandas)"
- "Make HTTP request using standard library only"

LIGHTWEIGHT
-----------
What it is:
- Small file size
- Fast to load
- Few dependencies

How to use:
- "Suggest a lightweight state management for React (avoid Redux)"
- "What's a lightweight alternative to Spring Boot?"

VENDOR-AGNOSTIC
---------------
What it is:
- Works on any cloud provider
- Not locked to AWS, Azure, or Google

How to use:
- "Write file upload code that is vendor-agnostic"
- "Design this service to be vendor-agnostic"

================================================================================
SECTION 4: DATA KEYWORDS
================================================================================

SEED
----
What it is:
- Number that controls random generation
- Same seed = same "random" results every time

Why use it:
- Reproducible test data
- Debugging with consistent data
- Sharing identical datasets

How to use:
- "Generate mock user data. Use a seed so I get same results"
- "Create random test data with seed 42"

SCHEMA
------
What it is:
- Structure of data, not the data itself
- Blueprint/template

Types:
- JSON Schema
- Database Schema
- API Schema (OpenAPI/Swagger)

How to use:
- "Generate a JSON Schema for a user profile"
- "Create database schema for e-commerce orders"

NORMALIZED vs DENORMALIZED
--------------------------
Normalized:
- No duplicate data
- Multiple related tables
- Data integrity
- Best for: transactional systems, source of truth

Denormalized:
- Data is repeated
- Single table/document
- Faster reads
- Best for: analytics, dashboards, search

How to use:
- "Design a normalized SQL schema for orders"
- "Create a denormalized view for reporting"

================================================================================
SECTION 5: STABILITY & OPERATIONS KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Critical for production scripts and DevOps.

IDEMPOTENT
----------
What it is:
- Safe to run multiple times
- Running once = running 100 times
- No additional side effects

Real-world analogy:
- Elevator button: pressing 10x doesn't call 10 elevators
- Thermostat: setting to 72 twice doesn't make it 144

How to use:
- "Write bash script to install Docker. Make it idempotent"
- "Ensure this migration script is idempotent"

Example (NOT idempotent - BAD):
echo "config" >> file.txt  # Adds line every time!

Example (idempotent - GOOD):
grep -q "config" file.txt || echo "config" >> file.txt

ATOMIC
------
What it is:
- All or nothing
- If any step fails, everything rolls back
- No partial completion

When critical:
- Financial transactions
- Database updates
- File operations

How to use:
- "Write money transfer function. Make it atomic"
- "Ensure database update is atomic"

GRACEFUL DEGRADATION
--------------------
What it is:
- If best option fails, use backup
- Never show error if you can show something

Examples:
- HD video fails → play SD video
- GPS unavailable → use IP location
- API timeout → show cached data

How to use:
- "Implement graceful degradation for video player"
- "Add fallback if primary API fails"

================================================================================
SECTION 6: ALGORITHMIC APPROACH KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Tell the AI HOW to solve the problem.

RECURSIVE
---------
What it is:
- Function calls itself
- Has base case (when to stop)
- Elegant but risk of stack overflow

Best for:
- Tree traversal
- Small datasets
- Problems with natural recursive structure

How to use:
- "Write recursive solution for tree traversal"
- "Solve this using recursion"

ITERATIVE
---------
What it is:
- Uses loops (for, while)
- Safer for large data
- Sometimes more verbose

Best for:
- Large datasets
- Performance critical code
- Avoiding stack overflow

How to use:
- "Use iterative approach to avoid stack overflow"
- "Convert this recursion to iterative"

GREEDY
------
What it is:
- Makes best choice at each step
- Doesn't look ahead
- Fast but not always optimal

How to use:
- "Write greedy algorithm for minimum coins"
- "Use greedy approach for this optimization"

BRUTE FORCE
-----------
What it is:
- Try every possible solution
- Simple but slow
- Always finds answer if one exists

When to use:
- Need quick working solution
- Verify clever solution is correct
- Small dataset

How to use:
- "First give brute force solution, then optimize"
- "What's the brute force approach here?"

================================================================================
SECTION 7: WEB & COMPATIBILITY KEYWORDS
================================================================================

POLYFILL
--------
What it is:
- Code that makes modern features work on old browsers
- Fills in missing functionality

How to use:
- "Include polyfill for Array.at() for older browsers"
- "Add polyfills for ES6 features"

MOBILE-FIRST
------------
What it is:
- Design for phones first
- Then scale up to desktop

How to use:
- "Generate CSS using mobile-first approach"
- "Design this layout mobile-first"

MINIFIED
--------
What it is:
- Compressed code (spaces, comments removed)
- Smaller file size for production

How to use:
- "Give me minified version of this JavaScript"
- "Output minified CSS"

RESPONSIVE
----------
What it is:
- Adapts to screen size
- Works on mobile and desktop

How to use:
- "Make this navigation bar responsive"
- "Create responsive grid layout"

================================================================================
SECTION 8: SECURITY KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Non-negotiable for production code.

OWASP TOP 10
------------
What it is:
- List of 10 most critical web security risks
- Industry standard checklist

The Top 10:
1. Broken Access Control
2. Cryptographic Failures
3. Injection (SQL, Command)
4. Insecure Design
5. Security Misconfiguration
6. Vulnerable Components
7. Authentication Failures
8. Data Integrity Failures
9. Logging Failures
10. Server-Side Request Forgery

How to use:
- "Review this login function against OWASP Top 10"
- "Check for OWASP vulnerabilities"

SANITIZE
--------
What it is:
- Clean user input
- Remove/escape dangerous characters
- Prevent injection attacks

How to use:
- "Sanitize all user inputs before database query"
- "Add input sanitization to this form"

LEAST PRIVILEGE
---------------
What it is:
- Give minimum permissions needed
- Nothing extra "just in case"

How to use:
- "Generate AWS IAM policy using least privilege"
- "Apply least privilege to database user"

ZERO TRUST
----------
What it is:
- Trust nobody by default
- Verify every request
- Even internal users authenticate

How to use:
- "Design API permissions using Zero Trust model"
- "Implement Zero Trust architecture"

SALT
----
What it is:
- Random data added to passwords before hashing
- Makes identical passwords hash differently

How to use:
- "Hash passwords with unique salt per user"
- "Add salt to password hashing"

================================================================================
SECTION 9: PERFORMANCE & CONCURRENCY KEYWORDS
================================================================================

RACE CONDITION
--------------
What it is:
- Two things happen simultaneously
- Result depends on timing
- Bugs that happen "sometimes"

How to use:
- "Check for race conditions in this code"
- "Prevent race condition when two users save"

LAZY LOADING
------------
What it is:
- Only load data when actually needed
- Don't load everything upfront

How to use:
- "Implement lazy loading for images"
- "Use lazy loading for dashboard data"

MEMOIZATION
-----------
What it is:
- Cache results of expensive calculations
- Return cached result for same input

How to use:
- "Optimize with memoization"
- "Add memoization to this recursive function"

N+1 PROBLEM
-----------
What it is:
- 1 query to get list
- N queries to get details for each item
- Very slow!

Fix: Eager loading, JOINs

How to use:
- "Check for N+1 problem in this ORM code"
- "Optimize this query to avoid N+1"

DEBOUNCE
--------
What it is:
- Wait until user STOPS doing something
- Then execute once

Use case: Search boxes

How to use:
- "Add debounce to search input"
- "Debounce API calls on keystroke"

THROTTLE
--------
What it is:
- Allow action only once per time period
- Ignore extra attempts

Use case: Scroll events, button clicks

How to use:
- "Throttle button clicks to prevent double-submit"
- "Add throttle to scroll handler"

EXPONENTIAL BACKOFF
-------------------
What it is:
- If fails, wait and retry
- Wait time doubles: 1s, 2s, 4s, 8s...

How to use:
- "Implement exponential backoff for API retries"
- "Add retry with exponential backoff"

MUTEX (Mutual Exclusion)
------------------------
What it is:
- Lock that prevents simultaneous access
- Only one thread at a time

How to use:
- "Protect shared variable with mutex"
- "Add mutex to prevent concurrent writes"

DEADLOCK
--------
What it is:
- Two processes wait for each other forever
- System freezes

How to use:
- "Check for potential deadlock scenarios"
- "Analyze for deadlock conditions"

NON-BLOCKING
------------
What it is:
- Code doesn't freeze while waiting
- Uses async/await

How to use:
- "Make this file upload non-blocking"
- "Convert to non-blocking async code"

COLD START
----------
What it is:
- Delay when serverless function wakes up
- First request is slow

How to use:
- "Optimize Lambda to minimize cold start"
- "Reduce cold start latency"

================================================================================
SECTION 10: TESTING KEYWORDS
================================================================================

SMOKE TEST
----------
What it is:
- Quick basic test
- Does system start at all?
- "Turn it on, see if smoke comes out"

How to use:
- "Write smoke test for health-check endpoint"
- "Create basic smoke test suite"

REGRESSION TEST
---------------
What it is:
- Tests that OLD features still work
- After adding NEW code

How to use:
- "Write regression tests for login after changes"
- "Add regression test for this feature"

MOCK
----
What it is:
- Fake version of real system
- Simulates behavior safely

Examples:
- Mock payment gateway
- Mock email server
- Mock external API

How to use:
- "Mock payment gateway for testing"
- "Create mock for external API"

FUZZING
-------
What it is:
- Throw random garbage at code
- See if it crashes
- Find unexpected bugs

How to use:
- "Write fuzzing script for input parser"
- "Fuzz test this validation function"

================================================================================
SECTION 11: REFACTORING KEYWORDS
================================================================================

EXTRACT METHOD
--------------
What it is:
- Take chunk of code
- Move to its own function
- Give clear name

How to use:
- "Apply Extract Method to validation logic"
- "Extract this code block into a function"

INLINE
------
What it is:
- Opposite of Extract Method
- Put function code directly where called

When to use:
- Function called only once
- Very short function

How to use:
- "Inline this helper function"
- "This is used once, inline it"

DE-COUPLE
---------
What it is:
- Break dependencies between modules
- Each part changes independently

How to use:
- "De-couple email from registration"
- "Reduce coupling between these classes"

================================================================================
SECTION 12: GIT & COLLABORATION KEYWORDS
================================================================================

CONVENTIONAL COMMITS
--------------------
What it is:
- Standardized commit message format
- Types: feat:, fix:, chore:, docs:

How to use:
- "Write commit message using Conventional Commits"
- "Format this as conventional commit"

CHANGELOG
---------
What it is:
- List of changes between versions

How to use:
- "Generate changelog from these commits"
- "Create changelog entry"

CONFLICT RESOLUTION
-------------------
How to use:
- "Suggest conflict resolution keeping both features"
- "Help resolve this merge conflict"

PULL REQUEST DESCRIPTION
------------------------
How to use:
- "Draft PR description for these changes"
- "Write pull request summary"

================================================================================
SECTION 13: API & INTEGRATION KEYWORDS
================================================================================

WEBHOOK
-------
What it is:
- Event listener that receives HTTP callbacks

How to use:
- "Write handler for Stripe webhook"
- "Create webhook endpoint"

PAYLOAD
-------
What it is:
- The data body being sent

How to use:
- "Construct JSON payload for this API"
- "Parse incoming payload"

ENDPOINT
--------
What it is:
- URL that accepts requests

How to use:
- "Create mock endpoint returning 500 error"
- "Design REST endpoints for users"

SWAGGER / OPENAPI
-----------------
What it is:
- Standard for documenting APIs

How to use:
- "Generate OpenAPI spec for this route"
- "Create Swagger documentation"

================================================================================
SECTION 14: DATA ENGINEERING KEYWORDS
================================================================================

ETL (Extract, Transform, Load)
------------------------------
What it is:
- Standard data pipeline process
- Extract from source
- Transform/clean
- Load to destination

How to use:
- "Write ETL script for this CSV to database"
- "Design ETL pipeline"

UPSERT (Update + Insert)
------------------------
What it is:
- Update if exists
- Insert if doesn't exist
- Prevents duplicates

How to use:
- "Write SQL upsert query"
- "Use upsert to avoid duplicates"

PIVOT
-----
What it is:
- Reshape data
- Rows become columns (or vice versa)

How to use:
- "Pivot this data so months are columns"
- "Unpivot this table"

BATCH PROCESSING
----------------
What it is:
- Handle data in chunks
- Not all at once
- Prevents memory issues

How to use:
- "Process in batches of 100 records"
- "Add batch processing to avoid memory crash"

