SECTION 17: AI ENGINEERING KEYWORDS
================================================================================

RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation)
------------------------------------
What it is:
- Feed AI your own data
- AI searches your docs to answer

How to use:
- "Implement basic RAG pipeline"
- "Build RAG system for documentation"

EMBEDDINGS
----------
What it is:
- Math representation of text
- Vectors for similarity search

How to use:
- "Convert text to embeddings"
- "Create embedding for semantic search"

INFERENCE
---------
What it is:
- Model actually running/thinking

How to use:
- "Optimize for faster inference"
- "Reduce inference latency"

TOKEN LIMIT
-----------
What it is:
- Maximum text length for AI model

How to use:
- "Truncate to fit 8k token limit"
- "Split text to respect token limit"

================================================================================
SECTION 18: CODE METRICS KEYWORDS
================================================================================

CYCLOMATIC COMPLEXITY
---------------------
What it is:
- Score of how many paths in code
- More if/else = higher score
- Lower is better

How to use:
- "Reduce cyclomatic complexity below 10"
- "Check cyclomatic complexity"

COGNITIVE COMPLEXITY
--------------------
What it is:
- How hard for HUMAN to understand
- Different from cyclomatic

How to use:
- "Lower cognitive complexity"
- "Simplify for readability"

CODE SMELL
----------
What it is:
- Patterns that are bad design
- Not bugs, but problems

Types:
- Long Method
- God Class
- Duplicate Code

How to use:
- "Check for code smells"
- "Identify code smells in this class"

================================================================================
SECTION 19: DATABASE INTERNALS KEYWORDS
================================================================================

INDEXING
--------
What it is:
- Speed up database searches
- Like book index

How to use:
- "Suggest indexing strategy for this query"
- "Add index to improve performance"

SHARDING
--------
What it is:
- Split database across servers

How to use:
- "Design sharding strategy for users table"
- "Implement database sharding"

ACID COMPLIANCE
---------------
What it is:
- Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability
- Data reliability guarantees

How to use:
- "Ensure ACID compliance"
- "Check if this supports ACID"

================================================================================
SECTION 20: CRYPTOGRAPHY & AUTH KEYWORDS
================================================================================

JWT (JSON Web Token)
--------------------
What it is:
- Token for keeping users logged in

How to use:
- "Write middleware to validate JWT"
- "Generate JWT for authentication"

SYMMETRIC vs ASYMMETRIC
-----------------------
Symmetric: Same key encrypts and decrypts
Asymmetric: Public/private key pair

How to use:
- "Use asymmetric encryption for this"
- "Implement symmetric encryption"

================================================================================
SECTION 21: CHAIN OF THOUGHT KEYWORDS
================================================================================

These make AI show its reasoning for better answers.

BASIC TRIGGERS
--------------
- "Think step by step"
- "Show your reasoning"
- "Explain your thinking"
- "Walk me through this"
- "Break this into smaller parts"

PLANNING
--------
- "First, summarize the problem"
- "List assumptions"
- "Create step-by-step plan"
- "Outline approach before coding"

VERIFICATION
------------
- "Check your work"
- "Verify each step"
- "Double-check the logic"
- "Look for edge cases"

STRUCTURED REASONING
--------------------
- "List the steps needed"
- "Weigh pros and cons"
- "Consider alternatives"
- "What could go wrong?"

================================================================================
SECTION 22: MASTER FORMULA & TEMPLATES
================================================================================

THE MASTER FORMULA
------------------
Combine one keyword from each category:

"Act as a [ROLE].
Write a [TASK]
using [CONSTRAINT]
that is [QUALITY].
Handle [DATA CONCERN].
Apply [SECURITY].
Output as [FORMAT].
Think step by step."

EXAMPLE USING FORMULA
---------------------
"Act as a Senior Backend Engineer.
Write a Python ETL script
using standard library only
that is idempotent and robust.
Handle edge cases like empty files.
Sanitize all inputs.
Output code with comments.
Think step by step and show your reasoning."

TEMPLATE: CODING TASK
---------------------
"Help me write [LANGUAGE] code.
Break the problem down into steps.
Explain your reasoning.
Then show the final code.
After the code, check for mistakes and edge cases."

TEMPLATE: DEBUGGING
-------------------
"This code has a bug: [describe bug]
Perform root cause analysis.
Trace the execution with input [X].
Explain why it fails.
Provide the fix with explanation."

TEMPLATE: ARCHITECTURE
----------------------
"I need to design [SYSTEM].
Act as a Senior Architect.
First, list the requirements and constraints.
Then, propose 2-3 approaches.
Compare pros and cons.
Recommend the best approach with reasoning."

TEMPLATE: CODE REVIEW
---------------------
"Review this code for:
- OWASP Top 10 security issues
- Code smells
- Performance problems (N+1, etc.)
- Edge cases not handled
Provide specific line numbers and fixes."

================================================================================
QUICK REFERENCE TABLE
================================================================================

| Phase        | Keywords                                        |
|--------------|-------------------------------------------------|
| Planning     | scaffold, skeleton, mock, design pattern        |
| Coding       | idiomatic, modular, type-safe, modern           |
| Data         | upsert, idempotent, atomic, ETL, normalized     |
| Security     | sanitize, OWASP, least privilege, zero trust    |
| Performance  | lazy loading, memoization, debounce, throttle   |
| Debug        | dry run, trace, root cause analysis             |
| Testing      | smoke test, regression, mock, fuzzing           |
| Quality      | edge cases, production-ready, robust            |
| Refactoring  | extract method, inline, de-couple               |

================================================================================
                              END OF GUIDE
================================================================================

Created for prompt engineering reference.
Use these keywords to get better, more precise results from AI assistants.

Remember: The more specific your vocabulary, the more expert-level
responses you'll receive.

================================================================================
                    COMPLETE PROMPT ENGINEERING GUIDE
                         For Junior Prompt Engineers
================================================================================

TABLE OF CONTENTS
-----------------
1. The Core Problem
2. The Hallucination-Proof Formula
3. The 5 Keyword Categories
4. The Fill-in-the-Blank Formula
5. Coding-Specific Keywords
6. Advanced Keywords
7. Practical Examples
8. Quick Reference Cards

================================================================================
PART 1: THE CORE PROBLEM
================================================================================

AI models are PROBABILISTIC — they predict the most likely next word.

This means:
  • Vague questions = vague (or invented) answers
  • Specific questions = accurate, useful answers

Your job as a prompt engineer is to STEER the AI in the right direction.

Think of keywords as STEERING WHEELS:
  • They tell the AI which direction to go
  • How fast to drive
  • What destination to reach

================================================================================
PART 2: THE HALLUCINATION-PROOF FORMULA
================================================================================

FORMULA:
--------
[Context/Data] + [Task] + [Strict Negative Constraint] + [Escape Hatch]

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMPONENT 1: CONTEXT (Grounding)
--------------------------------
Purpose: Provide the AI with the actual data to work with

BAD:  "What is the return policy of Company X?"
      (Relies on potentially outdated training data)

GOOD: "Context: [Paste the return policy text here]..."
      (AI works only with facts you control)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMPONENT 2: TASK
-----------------
Purpose: Tell the AI exactly what to do

Example: "Task: Summarize the refund timeline."

Be specific about the verb:
  • Instead of "help" → use "explain", "fix", "create"
  • Instead of "look at" → use "analyze", "review", "critique"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMPONENT 3: STRICT NEGATIVE CONSTRAINT
---------------------------------------
Purpose: Build a fence around the AI's behavior

Example: "Answer using only the information provided in the Context above. 
          Do not use outside knowledge."

This prevents the AI from mixing in random stuff from its training data.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMPONENT 4: ESCAPE HATCH (Crucial!)
------------------------------------
Purpose: Give the AI permission to stop instead of guessing

Example: "If the answer is not contained in the context, state 
          'Information not available'. Do not guess."

WHY THIS WORKS (Engineering View):
LLMs are probabilistic engines. When you ask a vague question, the 
"probability cloud" of potential answers is huge. By adding "If you 
don't know, say stop," you artificially boost the probability of the 
"Stop" token, making it statistically easier for the model to choose 
silence over creativity.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMPLETE EXAMPLE:
-----------------
"Context: [Paste refund policy here]

Task: Summarize the refund timeline.

Answer using only the information provided in the Context above. 
Do not use outside knowledge.

If the answer is not contained in the context, state 'Information 
not available'. Do not guess."

================================================================================
PART 3: THE 5 KEYWORD CATEGORIES
================================================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CATEGORY 1: IDENTITY KEYWORDS (Setting the Stage)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Purpose: Tell the AI WHO it should be (assigning a "Persona")

Keywords:
  • "Act as..."        → "Act as a senior software engineer"
  • "You are a..."     → "You are a strict editor"
  • "Simulate..."      → "Simulate a job interview for a marketing role"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CATEGORY 2: ACTION KEYWORDS (The Task)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Purpose: Be specific about the VERB you use

Instead of "Write," use:
  • Draft
  • Outline
  • Brainstorm
  • Compose
  • Script

Instead of "Look at," use:
  • Analyze
  • Critique
  • Proofread
  • Summarize
  • Extract

Instead of "Change," use:
  • Rephrase
  • Simplify
  • Translate
  • Expand
  • Condense

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CATEGORY 3: FORMAT KEYWORDS (The Output)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Purpose: Control the SHAPE of the answer

Keywords:
  • "Table"         → "Put this data into a table with columns for X, Y, Z"
  • "Bullet points" → "Summarize this using bullet points"
  • "Step-by-step"  → "Give me a step-by-step guide"
  • "Markdown"      → Great for formatting headers and bold text
  • "CSV"           → If you need data for Excel

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CATEGORY 4: TONE & AUDIENCE KEYWORDS (The Style)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Purpose: Control how the response "sounds"

Keywords:
  • "ELI5"              → Explain Like I'm 5 (simple language)
  • "Professional"      → Good for work emails
  • "Formal"            → Official documents
  • "Concise/Brief"     → Forces AI to cut out the fluff
  • "Empathetic"        → Good for difficult messages
  • "For a [Audience]"  → "Explain this for a beginner"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CATEGORY 5: CONSTRAINT KEYWORDS (The Guardrails)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Purpose: Stop the AI from rambling or doing things you don't want

Keywords:
  • "Only"          → "Give me the code only, no explanation"
  • "Limit to"      → "Limit to 3 sentences"
  • "Do not"        → "Do not use technical jargon"
  • "In the style of" → "Write this in the style of Shakespeare"

================================================================================
PART 4: THE FILL-IN-THE-BLANK FORMULA
================================================================================

THE PERFECT PROMPT FORMULA:
---------------------------
"Act as a [ROLE]...
 Create a [TASK]...
 Show it as [FORMAT]...
 And ensure you [CONSTRAINT/TONE]."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXAMPLE 1:
----------
"Act as a fitness coach. 
 Create a meal plan for next week. 
 Show it as a table with days of the week. 
 And ensure you include the calorie count for every meal."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXAMPLE 2 (Bad vs Good):
------------------------
BAD:  "Tell me how to make pasta."

GOOD: "Act as an Italian chef. 
       Explain how to make carbonara. 
       Write it for a complete beginner (ELI5). 
       Format the output as a step-by-step list. 
       Do not use cream."

================================================================================
PART 5: CODING-SPECIFIC KEYWORDS
================================================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THE "STACK" KEYWORDS (Context is King)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Always specify the language, framework, and version immediately.

  • "In [Language/Framework]..."  → "In Python 3.11...", "In React using TypeScript..."
  • "Using [Library]..."          → "Using the Pandas library...", "Using only standard library..."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THE "ACTION" KEYWORDS FOR CODING
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  • Refactor  → Rewrite code to be cleaner without changing functionality
  • Debug     → Find errors (Tip: paste error message AND code)
  • Optimize  → Focus on performance (speed or memory)
  • Document  → Add comments or generate docstrings
  • Convert   → Translate code from one language to another

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THE "CONSTRAINT" KEYWORDS FOR CODING
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  • "Code only"      → Stops intro/conclusion, just gives code block
  • "No explanation" → Strictly code
  • "Best practices" → Ensures code follows industry standards
  • "Edge cases"     → Handle weird scenarios (empty lists, nulls, negatives)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CODING EXAMPLES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

SCENARIO A: Writing New Code
-----------------------------
"Act as a Senior Java Developer. 
 Write a function that validates email addresses. 
 Use regular expressions. 
 Handle null inputs gracefully to avoid crashes. 
 Include Javadoc comments explaining the logic."

SCENARIO B: Debugging
---------------------
"Analyze the following Python code and the error message below. 
 Identify the root cause of the `IndexError`. 
 Propose a fix that checks the list length before accessing it.

 Code: [PASTE CODE]
 Error: [PASTE ERROR]"

SCENARIO C: Understanding Complex Code
--------------------------------------
"Explain this SQL query step-by-step. 
 Break down what each JOIN and WHERE clause is doing. 
 Add comments to the code to explain it for a junior developer."

SCENARIO D: Improving Existing Code
-----------------------------------
"Refactor this JavaScript function to make it cleaner and more readable. 
 Apply the DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle. 
 Convert it to use modern ES6 arrow syntax."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SPECIALIZED CODING PHRASES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Time Complexity / Big O:
  "Write a sorting algorithm. Ensure the Time Complexity is better than O(n^2)."

Test Cases:
  "Generate code for a calculator. Then, generate 5 unit test cases 
   to prove it works, including division by zero."

Mock Data:
  "Generate a CSV of mock employee data with columns: ID, Name, Salary. 
   Create 20 rows."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THE CODER'S SHORTCUT PROMPT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
For fastest results with no fluff:

"[Language]. [Task]. Code only."

Example: "Python. Script to parse a JSON file and save to CSV. Code only."

================================================================================
PART 6: ADVANCED KEYWORDS
================================================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
QUALITY & ROBUSTNESS KEYWORDS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  • "Production-ready" → Include error handling, logging, efficient logic
  • "Robust"           → Focus on preventing crashes
  • "Secure/Sanitize"  → Prevent SQL injection, XSS, etc.
  • "Scalable"         → Code that works with small AND large data

Examples:
  "Write a production-ready Python script to upload files to S3."
  "Make this API call robust against network timeouts."
  "Write a SQL query to update users, but sanitize inputs to prevent injection."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ARCHITECTURE & DESIGN KEYWORDS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  • "Design Pattern" → Use Singleton, Factory, Observer, etc.
  • "Modular"        → Break code into small, reusable functions
  • "RESTful"        → Specific to API design

Examples:
  "Implement a logger class using the Singleton design pattern."
  "Write a web scraper, but keep it modular so I can reuse the parsing logic."
  "Create a RESTful API endpoint for creating a new user."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
MODERNIZATION KEYWORDS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  • "Modern"            → Use latest syntax
  • "Deprecation-free"  → Don't use functions being removed
  • "Functional"        → Immutability, pure functions
  • "Object-Oriented"   → Classes, inheritance

Examples:
  "Rewrite this JavaScript using modern ES6+ syntax."
  "Solve this problem using a functional programming approach."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
EXPLANATION & LEARNING KEYWORDS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  • "Annotate"  → Line-by-line explanation
  • "Compare"   → Compare libraries or approaches
  • "Skeleton"  → Basic structure without inner logic
  • "Scaffold"  → Project setup with folders and placeholder files
  • "Rationale" → Explain WHY choices were made

Examples:
  "Annotate every line of this complex regex pattern."
  "Compare 'Requests' vs 'Httpx' libraries in Python for async performance."
  "Create a project skeleton for a Flask app with blueprint structure."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TESTING KEYWORDS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  • "Happy Path"  → Scenario where everything goes right
  • "Edge Cases"  → Weird scenarios (empty, null, negative)
  • "TDD"         → Test Driven Development (write test before code)

Examples:
  "Write a test for the happy path."
  "Now write tests covering the edge cases."
  "Using TDD, write a function that calculates Fibonacci numbers."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THE "IDIOMATIC" KEYWORD
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Purpose: Use language-specific features properly ("native speaker" code)

WITHOUT "idiomatic" (generic/C-style Python):
  numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
  even_numbers = []
  for i in range(len(numbers)):
      if numbers[i] % 2 == 0:
          even_numbers.append(numbers[i])

WITH "idiomatic" (Pythonic):
  numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
  even_numbers = [num for num in numbers if num % 2 == 0]

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THE "SCAFFOLD" KEYWORD
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Purpose: Build project skeleton quickly

Prompt:
"Generate a project scaffold for a Node.js Express API. 
 Include a standard folder structure and create placeholder files 
 for routes and controllers. Do not implement the business logic yet."

Result:
  /my-api
    /src
      /controllers
        userController.js
      /routes
        userRoutes.js
      app.js
    package.json

================================================================================
PART 7: PRACTICAL EXAMPLES BY USE CASE
================================================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FOR PROFESSIONAL WRITING (Emails & Reports)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"Act as a senior project manager. 
 Draft a concise email to the client updating them on the delay. 
 Tone should be professional but reassuring. 
 Limit to 150 words."

"Proofread this attached report. 
 Fix grammar errors and rephrase awkward sentences. 
 Do not change the technical meaning."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FOR LEARNING NEW TOPICS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"Explain 'Cloud Computing' for a 12-year-old (ELI5). 
 Use analogies involving a library to make it easy to understand."

"Simulate a job interview for a Junior Developer role. 
 Ask me one question at a time. 
 Wait for my answer before asking the next one."

"I want to understand how a car engine works. 
 Let's think step by step. 
 Start from when I turn the key."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FOR ORGANIZING DATA OR RESEARCH
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"Analyze the text below. 
 Extract all names, dates, and locations. 
 Format the output as a Markdown table with those three headers."

"Compare the iPhone 15 and the Samsung S24. 
 List the pros and cons of each in bullet points. 
 Focus only on camera and battery life."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FOR CREATIVE TASKS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"Act as a travel agent. 
 Plan a 3-day itinerary for Tokyo. 
 Include vegetarian restaurants. 
 Format the itinerary as a time-based schedule."

"Write a scary story in the style of Stephen King. 
 Keep the ending ambiguous."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
HANDLING THE "ABSOLUTE AUTHORITY" PROBLEM
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
When asking about obscure topics/people that might not exist:

BAD (Assumes existence):
"Who is John Doe from Smalltown, Ohio?"
(Risk: AI invents a persona)

GOOD (Conditional Logic):
"Step 1: Search your database for a 'John Doe' from 'Smalltown, Ohio'. 
 Step 2: If and only if you find a high-confidence match with a public 
         record, summarize his biography. 
 Step 3: If you cannot find a clear match, simply say 'No public record found'."

================================================================================
PART 8: QUICK REFERENCE CARDS
================================================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
HALLUCINATION-PROOF FORMULA
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Component      | Purpose              | Example                            |
|----------------|----------------------|------------------------------------|
| Context        | Ground in facts      | "Here is the data: [paste]"        |
| Task           | Specific action      | "Summarize the key points"         |
| Constraint     | Set boundaries       | "Use only this data"               |
| Escape Hatch   | Permission to stop   | "If unsure, say 'unknown'"         |

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5 KEYWORD CATEGORIES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Category    | Purpose                  | Examples                          |
|-------------|--------------------------|-----------------------------------|
| Identity    | Who should AI be?        | "Act as...", "You are a..."       |
| Action      | What verb to perform?    | Analyze, Draft, Refactor, Debug   |
| Format      | What should output be?   | Table, Bullet points, Step-by-step|
| Tone        | How should it sound?     | Concise, Professional, ELI5       |
| Constraint  | What are the limits?     | "Only...", "Do not...", "Limit to"|

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CODING KEYWORDS SUMMARY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Goal        | Keyword                  | Effect                            |
|-------------|--------------------------|-----------------------------------|
| Safety      | Sanitize, Secure         | Prevents vulnerabilities          |
| Quality     | Production-ready         | Adds error handling and logging   |
| Structure   | Modular, Design Pattern  | Organizes code logically          |
| Style       | Modern, Idiomatic        | Uses correct way for that language|
| Speed       | Boilerplate, Scaffold    | Generates setup code quickly      |
| Testing     | Happy Path, Edge Cases   | Ensures code reliability          |

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THE MAGIC PHRASE FOR LOGIC PROBLEMS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"Let's think step by step."

Forces AI to show reasoning, catches errors in math and logic.

================================================================================
                              END OF GUIDE
================================================================================

Remember: Keywords are steering wheels, not magic spells.
They tell the AI exactly which direction to go, how fast to drive, 
and what destination to reach.

Practice building prompts using the formulas, and you'll see 
immediate improvement in AI responses!



